BACKEND AGENT ‚Äì MASTER RULES & INTEGRATION SPEC
CodeArena: FastAPI, Postgres, Redis, WebSockets
The backend is a FastAPI application with async Postgres + Redis, JWT auth, REST APIs for core data, and WebSockets for real‚Äëtime battles. It must match the frontend and product specs exactly.

1. Tech Stack & Structure
Language / Framework: Python 3.11+, FastAPI.
‚Äã

Database: PostgreSQL via SQLAlchemy 2.0 (async, asyncpg driver).
‚Äã

Cache / Realtime infra: Redis 7+ for caching, matchmaking queues, battle state, and pub/sub.
‚Äã

Auth: JWT (HS256) with bcrypt password hashing.
‚Äã

Execution: separate worker/sandbox (Wasm or Docker) reached asynchronously via queue; API never runs untrusted code inline.
‚Äã

Filesystem (conceptual):

app/main.py ‚Äì FastAPI app, middleware, health, router registration.
‚Äã

app/core/ ‚Äì database, redis, security, config, dependencies.
‚Äã

app/models/ ‚Äì SQLAlchemy models: User, Algorithm/Organism, Problem/Challenge, Battle/Match, Submission, etc.
‚Äã

app/schemas/ ‚Äì Pydantic schemas for all REST endpoints.
‚Äã

app/services/ ‚Äì BattleManager, Matchmaker, ChallengeService, UserService, SubmissionService, etc.
‚Äã

app/api/v1/ ‚Äì route modules: auth.py, users.py, algorithms.py, battles.py, problems.py, matchmaking.py, submissions.py, leaderboard.py.

app/workers/ ‚Äì background workers (matchmaker loop, code_executor queue consumer).
‚Äã

All new code must plug into this structure; no new random folders.

2. Core Infrastructure Wiring
2.1 Database Layer
Connection URL built as postgresql+asyncpg://USER:PASS@HOST:PORT/DBNAME.
‚Äã

create_async_engine with:

pool_size=10, max_overflow=20, pool_pre_ping=True, pool_recycle=3600.
‚Äã

AsyncSessionLocal via sessionmaker, expire_on_commit=False.
‚Äã

get_db() dependency yields an AsyncSession and:

commits on success, rollbacks on exception, always closes.
‚Äã

Usage in endpoints:

python
@router.get("/users")
async def list_users(db: AsyncSession = Depends(get_db)):
    result = await db.execute(select(User))
    return result.scalars().all()
All DB access from routes must use get_db() and never create ad‚Äëhoc engines.

2.2 Redis Layer
Global redis_client = redis.from_url(REDIS_URL, decode_responses=True, max_connections=50, ...).
‚Äã

get_redis() dependency yields this client.
‚Äã

Use Redis for:

Matchmaking queues (sorted sets).

Leaderboards (sorted sets).
‚Äã

Battle state snapshots and tick deltas.
‚Äã

Pub/sub channels for notifying WebSockets and workers.
‚Äã

3. Authentication & Security
Passwords:

Hashed with bcrypt via CryptContext (rounds=12).
‚Äã

JWT:

HS256, payload has sub (user id), exp, iat, type="access".
‚Äã

Access token lifetime ~30 min, refresh token ~7 days.
‚Äã

verify_token() decodes and validates JWT; raises 401 for invalid/expired.
‚Äã

Dependencies:

python
async def get_current_user(
    token: str = Depends(oauth2_scheme),
    db: AsyncSession = Depends(get_db)
) -> User:
    payload = verify_token(token)
    user_id = payload.get("sub")
    # load user, ensure active, else raise HTTPException(401/403)
All protected routes must depend on get_current_user; admin actions also depend on require_admin().
‚Äã

Frontend integration:

Frontend stores tokens (currently in localStorage) and sends them as Authorization: Bearer <token> headers via Axios interceptors.
‚Äã

401 ‚Üí frontend attempts refresh token flow, then redirects to /login on failure.
‚Äã

4. High‚ÄëLevel API Surface
Backend must provide:

Auth: signup, login, logout, refresh, current user.

Users: get profile, stats, settings.

Problems/Challenges: list, detail, metadata for coding page.

Algorithms / Organisms: CRUD for algorithm entities, stats, traits, death count.

Matchmaking & Battles:

Join quick match queue.

Monitor queue position/estimated wait.

Create battle and connect via WebSocket.

Get battle history / battle detail.

Submissions & Code Execution:

run for sample tests (fast feedback).

submit for full evaluation and scoring.

Leaderboards: user ELO, streaks, algorithm rankings.

All routes must respond with consistent JSON:

json
{
  "success": true,
  "data": { ... },
  "message": "Optional human-readable message"
}
and on error:

json
{
  "success": false,
  "error": {
    "code": "ERROR_CODE",
    "message": "Human readable",
    "details": { ...optional... }
  }
}
5. Detailed Endpoint Logic & Frontend Wiring
Below is what each major endpoint does and how the frontend calls it.

5.1 Auth Routes (/api/v1/auth/...)
POST /auth/signup
Input: username, email, password.
Logic:

Validate uniqueness, hash password, create user.
‚Äã

Issue access & refresh tokens and return user profile.
‚Äã

Frontend: authService.signup() then stores tokens and user in context.
‚Äã

POST /auth/login
Input: email/username, password.
Logic:

Verify password, issue tokens, return user.
‚Äã

Frontend: authService.login(), update AuthContext, redirect to /dashboard.
‚Äã

GET /auth/me

Returns current user profile (UserProfile + UserStats).

Used on app load to refresh auth state.
‚Äã

