5.3 Algorithms / Organisms (/api/v1/algorithms)
GET /algorithms (user‚Äôs algorithms)

Uses get_current_user and returns all living algorithms belonging to the user.

Fields: id, name, language, stats, traits, generation, is_alive, death_count.

POST /algorithms
Input: Pydantic model AlgorithmCreate (code, language, optional names/metadata).

Logic:

Validate input, sanitize code (forbidden imports, etc.).
‚Äã

Insert into algorithms table with default stats and generation=1.
‚Äã

This is used when user ‚Äúbirths‚Äù a new organism.

GET /algorithms/{id}

Detail view for showing organism profile and history (later used in dashboard/algorithms page).
‚Äã

Backend must enforce permadeath:

Before queueing an algorithm for battle or evolution, check is_alive and death_count < 3; otherwise reject with ERROR_CODE = "ALGORITHM_DEAD".

5.4 Matchmaking & Quick Match (/api/v1/matchmaking / /battles/queue)
Matchmaker service already exists but is not fully wired; backend must integrate it.
‚Äã

POST /matchmaking/queue/join
Input: mode (e.g., "ranked_1v1"), difficulty, language, algorithm_id.

Logic:

Validate:

User is authenticated.
‚Äã

Algorithm belongs to user, alive, correct language.

Get user ELO from DB.
‚Äã

MatchmakerService.add_to_queue(user_id, difficulty, language, elo):

Adds to Redis ZSET queue:{difficulty}:{language} with ELO as score.
‚Äã

Optionally returns position and queue size.
‚Äã

Return queue info to frontend.

Frontend:

Quick Match button on Dashboard or Problems page calls this endpoint.
‚Äã

UI shows ‚ÄúIn queue ‚Äì position X of Y, est wait ~Ns‚Äù.

POST /matchmaking/queue/leave

Uses MatchmakerService.remove_from_queue(user_id) to remove from all relevant queues.
‚Äã

Background process:

Worker app/workers/matchmaker.py runs process_matchmaking() in a loop:

For each queue key:

Load queued players (sorted by ELO).
‚Äã

Call find_best_match to pair players by ELO difference & wait time.
‚Äã

When a match pair is found:

Create a battle record in DB.
‚Äã

Initialize BattleManager state in Redis.
‚Äã

Publish notification on Redis channel match:{user_id}.
‚Äã

Frontend:

Dashboard or ‚Äúqueue waiting‚Äù view opens a WebSocket / SSE or polls API:

Option A: WebSocket on ws://.../matchmaking subscribing to match:{user_id} via backend.

Option B: Poll /matchmaking/status until battle is created.

On notification, frontend navigates to /battles/{battle_id}.

5.5 Battles (/api/v1/battles + WebSocket /ws/battles/{id})
REST endpoints:

GET /battles

Filter by status, pagination; used for Battles history page.

GET /battles/{battle_id}

Returns summary of one battle: players, problem, scores, timing, pointers to submissions and replay data.

WebSocket endpoint:

@router.websocket("/ws/battles/{battle_id}")
Logic:

Authenticate user via JWT in query/header/cookie.

Verify user is participant or authorized spectator.

Use BattleManager to either:

create battle state (if first join), or

attach this socket to an existing battle room.
‚Äã

Start the tick loop for this battle if not already started.
‚Äã

Receive messages:

CODE_UPDATE ‚Äì pass to BattleManager.update_player_code(...).
‚Äã

RUN_TESTS ‚Äì queue execution task for sample tests.
‚Äã

SUBMIT ‚Äì queue full execution, mark player as submitted.
‚Äã

Send messages (deltas) from BattleManager back to connected clients:

Timer updates, test progress, submission status, winner/loser, etc.
‚Äã

Frontend integration:

Coding arena page (ProblemDetail when in match context) opens WebSocket to /ws/battles/{id} once battle is assigned.
‚Äã

Local Monaco editor still controls the text, but:

Selected ops (e.g., run/submit) are sent via WebSocket messages rather than plain REST when inside a live battle.

Opponent‚Äôs cursor/test progress are visualized using deltas from server.

5.6 Submissions & Execution (/api/v1/submissions/run, /submit)
POST /submissions/run (sample tests)

Input: challenge_id, code, language.
‚Äã

Logic:

Validate code and language via SubmissionCreate schema (sanitizes language and ensures length constraints).
‚Äã

Create a submission record with status PENDING.
‚Äã

Push job to execution queue (Redis list / SQS style) with:

submission id, code, language, test_cases (sample only), resource limits.
‚Äã

Return a submission id and maybe initial ‚Äúqueued‚Äù status to frontend.

POST /submissions/submit (full evaluation)

Same as run but uses full test suite (including hidden tests) and marks battle logic when done.

Execution worker (app/workers/code_executor.py):

Listens to code_execution_tasks queue in Redis.
‚Äã

For each job:

Spawns sandbox (Docker or Wasm host), runs code with timeout and memory cap.
‚Äã

Collects results: per test case pass/fail, stdout/stderr, runtime, memory.
‚Äã

Updates submission record with result summary (ACCEPTED, WRONG_ANSWER, TIME_LIMIT, etc.) and metrics.
‚Äã

If battle‚Äëlinked:

Notifies BattleManager or pushes pub/sub to WebSocket channel.
‚Äã

If just practice:

Optionally notifies WebSocket or stores for GET /submissions/{id} polling.

Frontend:

CodeEditorPanel:

On ‚ÄúRun Code‚Äù: calls /submissions/run, shows spinner, then polls /submissions/{id} or waits for WebSocket update to render test results.
‚Äã

On ‚ÄúSubmit‚Äù: similar but triggers ‚Äúaccepted/failed‚Äù states and roasts/replays.
‚Äã

6. Services & Business Logic
6.1 BattleManager (authoritative state)
Maintains:

In‚Äëmemory map of active battles + state.

Background tick loop at 20 Hz (every 50 ms) per active battle.
‚Äã

Each tick:

Decrements timer, checks win conditions and timeouts.
‚Äã

Saves updated state to Redis.
‚Äã

Computes minimal deltas between previous and new state and broadcasts over WebSocket channels to all clients in that battle.
‚Äã

Delta example:

json
{
  "type": "STATE_DELTA",
  "tick": 1234,
  "timer_remaining_seconds": 672.5,
  "players": {
    "player1_id": { "tests_passed": 5 },
    "player2_id": { "tests_passed": 3 }
  }
}
6.2 MatchmakerService
Uses Redis ZSETs queue:{difficulty}:{language} with ELO as score; pairs nearest ELO players first, with relax rules if wait time > 2 minutes.
‚Äã

Creates matches in DB and cleans them from queues; interacts with WebSockets via pub/sub.
‚Äã

6.3 ChallengeService
Wraps DB + Redis caching for listing and retrieving problems.
‚Äã

Used by REST routes instead of raw DB queries, to centralize caching and invalidation.
‚Äã

7. Frontend‚ÄìBackend Contract Summary
Base URL: backend exposes HTTP on http://localhost:8001 (dev) and paths like /api/v1/...; frontend uses VITE_API_BASE_URL + ENDPOINTS config (/api/v1/auth/login, /api/v1/challenges, etc.).
‚Äã

Auth:

Bearer token in headers, refresh on 401, redirect to /login if refresh fails.

Coding flow:

Frontend calls GET /challenges/:id to populate problem + starter code.

On ‚ÄúRun Code‚Äù, frontend calls /submissions/run and shows returned results.

On ‚ÄúSubmit‚Äù, calls /submissions/submit, then:

If solo: show accepted/failed and store as history.

If in battle: uses WebSocket updates to show who won and update scoreboard.
‚Äã

Battles:

REST for history & detail, WebSocket for real‚Äëtime.

Matchmaking:

REST to join/leave queue; either WebSocket or polling to detect created battle.

8. Backend Non‚ÄëGoals
Do not include cloud‚Äëprovider‚Äëspecific infra code (Terraform, Helm) here; DevOps is handled separately.
‚Äã

Do not execute untrusted user code directly in FastAPI request handlers; always push to the execution worker queue.
‚Äã

Do not expose raw internal models to frontend; always wrap with Pydantic schemas that match the agreed response formats.

